Wolvish for Human-Wolf Couples: FAQ GUIDE
>Why do wolves speak the way they do?
I've discussed this before, but you've gotta think of this from a anthro-linguistic point of view.
Take my girlfriend for example. Pure wolf, came from ForestLandia, never grew up speaking English. She and her ancestors have a completely different mouth architecture, so they ended up creating words that were easy for them so say physically.
>What sounds should I expect to hear and replicate if I'm trying to learn Wolvish?
Wolfspeak is inevitably going to contain a lot more of "R" "RR" "W" "OO" "O" "Uh" "A" "F" "M" and "P" sounds.
That's why every wolf girl you meet has some name like "Warra" or "Mawoona" or "Wurrf" . It's the architecture of the muzzle that guides them to certain sounds.
>My wolf girlfriend is whining a lot. Is she mad at me?
No! Well, probably not. See, wolf-types use whines in their language as actual sounds. (My gf stresses them a lot more when she's hungry or horny. Very important for communication. So get the hint guys! Ask her what she needs!)
Many dialects of wolvish also use snarls as well. She's not on her period all the time, she's just talking.

>What if I can't understand everything my wolf gf says?
You're going to have to trust her. I'll give you a personal anecdote:
The other day I was looking at my babe's texts over her shoulder as she wrote to her family. Basically I converted the Wolvish words to their English approximations (this way of writing wolfspeak is called "humanji") it was more of the same. She texted
>"Whurrf whineeorra muparro moof"
and I had no idea what this means.
I can understand her when she wants to be understood, but Zoogle translate has notoriously bad support for her family's dialect.

Long story short, the translator gave me misinformation and I thought she was cheating on me! I got super upset with her and she had to explain to me some of the regional differences on her side of the woods.

>My wolf gf is trying to learn English, but only knows wolfspeak. How can I help?
Just be a supportive boyfriend. Don't scold or correct her all the time. Reward her for remembering words, with pats/scritches. Be patient and use the full names of things instead of "it" so that she learns them. Speak clearly for her.
>Will my wifwolf have the accent forever or am I going to have to play translator at my parents' house?
She'll carry some accent forever. Even wolves born in English-speaking territories can't get over the physical hurdles of having a muzzle.

>What specific hurdles?
They struggle with the "EE" sound and often replace it with a little whine.
The "V" sound can also be problematic, just because it's harder for wolves to make all their top teeth touch the bottom lip.
When she makes an "R" sound it's going to sound a lot more nasally because of her larger nasal cavity. Think Portuguese.
There are lots of others title things like that.
On the plus side, wolves are surprisingly adept at making both "TH" sounds in English, by using their long tongues and baring the top teeth. Most other cultures have a hard time with it.

>Any other tips on communicating with my wifwolf?
Yes! Communication =/= speaking, and body language is CRUCIAL with wolves.
Watch her ears and tail, the same way you watch hand gestures when someone speaks.
Wolves don't have the strong cheek muscles we do, so there's less information they can convey with smiles. This gets expressed via tail, ear, and neck motions.
-Wagging tails, active upright ears, and exposed necks are great indicators of comfort, agreement and other positive emotions.
-Flattened ears, stiff tails, raised hackles and highly exposed teeth, indicate distrust, confusion, and anger.
-Bonus Gesture: If she grabs your penis, she wants to have intercourse with you.

Thank you for reading this brief guide on the linguistic issues of Human-Wolf couples. I wish you all happy marriages and healthy litters.

>What is something cool you want your character to do?
Or
>What is something cute/funny/serious your characters would do interacting with each other?
You now have the premise of a scene. The hard part is getting there, and describing it. It doesn't have to be super unique and original either. Make character tell jokes that you know, or reenact scenes that you've seen (with enough personal flair for it not to be recognizable). Just be sure it fits the tone, and character consistency.
Hell, throw in a few things that you yourself have experienced. That's great for description, especially if it's something specific that very few people know what it feels like.
